everlasting-general.notes: The prolific 1/2- 3/4" silvery-white blooms on stiff stems are typically grown for dried-flower production but are also useful as fresh cuts for flower arrangements. The tiny blooms make an elegant addition to boutonnieres and floral crowns. As flowers mature, the papery white petals open to reveal bright-yellow centers. Flowers are typically harvested when half open, before the center is exposed. Winged Everlasting gets its name from ribbed, or winged stems the plant produces. Tender perennial in Zones 9-10 but most often grown as an annual. Once the flowers were fully open at our trial farm, we noticed lots of flying friends visiting the flowers, including hoverflies and wasps.

4-7 days @ 65 degrees. 

Hortonova — optional. We find Hortonova to interfere with harvesting pansies and violas, so we no longer use it as support in this crop. However, depending on your preference, it can be useful for supporting taller varieties.   Brush Strokes: Earliest variety in our trials to have long enough stems to harvest. Nature Series: Almost as early as Brush Strokes; tall productive plants with beautiful color range. Frizzle Sizzle Series: later than Brush Strokes and slightly shorter, with unique, deeply ruffled blooms.  Sorbet Formula Mix: Best choice for edible flower production. This variety had the most consistent bloom production through the winter and early spring.   Stems stretch as the days lengthen, yielding harvestable (10–20") stems suitable for mixing into spring bouquets. Long harvest window.   Plants bloomed throughout the winter, yielding edible flowers on short, compact plants. Once the days began to lengthen, stems started to stretch. We found this crop particularly valuable in early May, paired with field tulips and daffodils. The flowers added sparkle and the leafy stems added nice greenery in pairings with the early bulb crops.  * If growing for edible blooms:  Sorbet Formula Mix yielded blooms December through March, with best and most consistent production in late February through March.

potato-early.name: Early
potato-early.notes: If the leaves go yellow they are definitely ready to harvest. Flowering can be a sign that they are nearing harvest but not always. No big need to plant them early as cold weather often sets them back and later plantings will catch up. Most efficient to water them near harvest, but unless it's especially dry they can be dry-farmed. Additional water will help increase yields. Brown leaves aren't blight, they generally go more translucent. Potatoes will come out cleaner if the soil is not wet. Dowding yields almost 13 kilos out of his small beds. One of our rows is likely around 5 of those. So we should be able to get 130 lb out of a 50 ft bed if we can get things dialed.

radicchio-110-day.name: 110 Day
radicchio-110-day.notes: Sew in trays around summer solstice (June 21st) through the first third of July says Osborne. Many varieties are differentiated by the DTM. Hard to grow, but doesn't sound like rocket science. Longer varieties are more cold hardy. 30 minutes in. https://www.notillgrowers.com/blog/2019/12/23/the-no-till-market-garden-podcast-with-evan-chendar-the-culinary-gardener. Hard to get dense heads which are necessary to get good texture, blanched color. Shorter varieties are easier to get a hit on. Nights in the 40s to head up for large varieties. Need gradual weather. Outer leaves self blanch when you force it. Forcing always develops a dense head. Even early varieties are cold hardy to 15 deg with AG-19 over short stints. Easy to force in water. Dig plants. trim slightly. Pack in crates insides a tub with a few inches of water + a heater under a lower tunnel raised on pallets. Force for three weeks. Change water twice a week. All nonf-roced are 6/lb. Forced are 20/lb. Target head is 0.5 lb up to 2lb. Sounds like early varieties are grown on 10 inch spacing. Why do the heads big? It seems riskier to do them larger and you can't fit as many to the bed. Seems better to do smaller tighter. Young Plants hardy to 5 deg. Mature hardy to 23 deg. Late-maturing varieties store longer than short-season varieties. https://www.osborneseed.com/catalog/cp_/catalog/vegetables/chicory/radicchio. Remay below 25. Possible to Spring force radicchio (would be less sweet but easier to heat)? https://uprisingorganics.com/pages/radicchiology https://extension.colostate.edu/docs/pubs/garden/07617.pdf. Assumune 2 lbs per plant. Typically plant less than three weeks before first frost. Much of the U.S. can plant in late march if fleeced. Midseason get planted in late april. Main crop get planted in mid apr - mid may. Earlier go late march - June. Midseason go late apr - late jul. Main crop go mid apr - mid may through aug. Heading varieties (Chioggia, Verona, Treviso precoce, Lusia, Rosa) are better sown towards the earlier part of this window. Looser or more cold tolerant varieties (Gorizia/Isontina, Castelfranco, Treviso Tardivo, Catalogna) or the earliest slotted varieties of the heading types, have more flexibility and can be successfully sown later in the window. Grumolo (a late winter/early spring harvested variety) can be sown into August. rosemary-general.name: General
rosemary-general.notes: Most nurseries grow rosemary from cuttings, not seeds. Germination is notoriously low, so plant more seeds than needed. Sow them barely covered with sterilized seed starting mix over bottom heat. Once germinated, rosemary is highly prone to damping off, so keep watering to a minimum, provide bright light, and ventilation. Keep each plant in its own pot for the first winter and offer them protection from severe cold. Transplant to the garden the following spring at a spacing of 60-90cm (24-36″).

Harden off and transplant outside after the last frost. Direct seed - Successive plantings every 2-3 weeks until late spring give the best quality flowers and pods. May require support.

Airflow and low light penetration are key to reducing mold problems. Thnnings can be a valuable extra crop. Sell 10 in a bag for $10 or pot up. Might be able to fall plant in our climate but there's some risk of plants dying. Drought sensitive but only require irrigation in drought conditions.
